  "prompt": "What do Jews think of John the Baptist?",
  "response": "Jews generally view John the Baptist (Yochanan ben Zechariah) as a historical Jewish figure and a prophet, but they do not see him in the same messianic or religious context as Christians do. In Jewish tradition:\n\n1. John is seen as a Jewish religious leader and prophet who lived during the Second Temple period.\n\n2. He is recognized as a contemporary of Jesus and a preacher who called for spiritual renewal and repentance.\n\n3. Jewish scholars acknowledge his role in promoting ritual immersion (baptism) and moral righteousness.\n\n4. However, Jews do not accept the Christian belief that John was a forerunner to Jesus or a messianic figure.\n\n5. He is viewed as one of many Jewish prophets and religious leaders of his time, significant in his historical context but not possessing supernatural or messianic status.\n\nMost Jews respect John as a historical Jewish religious figure but do not attribute to him the theological significance that Christians do.",
